{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522795"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:48:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:48:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13847"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13847"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.55,0.02,0.02,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6464"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48889"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6464"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13847"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33887"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"2634"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11605"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12787"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30601"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42947"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48889"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of headache, dizziness, and nausea. She works as a forklift operator in an enclosed warehouse. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears mildly distressed with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Her neurological examination is normal. Blood tests reveal a carboxyhaemoglobin level of 25% (0-3).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hyperbaric oxygen therapy","High-flow oxygen via non-rebreather mask","Intubation and mechanical ventilation","Intravenous N-acetylcysteine","Observation on room air"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is presenting with symptoms consistent with carbon monoxide (CO) poisoning, likely due to exposure in her enclosed workplace. The elevated carboxyhaemoglobin level confirms the diagnosis. The most appropriate initial management for CO poisoning is \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh-flow oxygen via non-rebreather mask\u003C/strong\u003E. This treatment accelerates the dissociation of CO from haemoglobin, reducing its half-life from about 4-5 hours on room air to about 60-90 minutes on 100% oxygen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperbaric oxygen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered in severe cases of CO poisoning, particularly in pregnant patients or those with neurological symptoms, loss of consciousness, or very high carboxyhaemoglobin levels (typically \u0026gt;25%). While this patient\u0027s level is 25%, she does not have severe neurological symptoms, and high-flow oxygen should be initiated first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntubation and mechanical ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E would be necessary only if the patient had a decreased level of consciousness or was unable to protect her airway. This patient is alert and has normal neurological examination findings, so intubation is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous N-acetylcysteine\u003C/strong\u003E is used in the treatment of paracetamol overdose, not CO poisoning. It has no role in the management of this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation on room air\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate for treating CO poisoning. The patient requires high-flow oxygen to accelerate the elimination of CO from her system and prevent further tissue hypoxia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["High-flow oxygen therapy is the first-line treatment for carbon monoxide poisoning.","Carboxyhaemoglobin levels do not always correlate with clinical severity in carbon monoxide poisoning.","Hyperbaric oxygen therapy may be considered in severe cases of carbon monoxide poisoning, particularly in pregnant patients or those with neurological symptoms."],"references":["Carbon Monoxide Poisoning. In: Life in the Fast Lane [online]. 2019. Available at: https://litfl.com/carbon-monoxide-poisoning/","\u200cEichhorn L, Thudium M, J\u00fcttner B. The Diagnosis and Treatment of Carbon Monoxide Poisoning. Dtsch Arztebl Int. 2018 Dec 24;115(51-52):863-870. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6381775/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33887"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13847"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33887"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-19T13:11:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-04T13:45:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6464"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48889"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://a